  "prompt": "What is the maximum number of tabs open in Google or Computer?",
  "response": "The maximum number of tabs you can open in Google Chrome or any web browser largely depends on system resources such as RAM and CPU, rather than a strict limit set by the browser itself. \n\n1. **Technical Limits**: While there isn't an official maximum number of tabs, practical limits are usually in the range of several hundred to a few thousand tabs, depending on your computer's specifications. For example, with 8 GB of RAM, you might comfortably run around 200-300 tabs, but performance can degrade as more tabs are opened.\n\n2. **Browser Limitations**: Some browsers may impose their own arbitrary limits for performance reasons, but these limits are typically much higher than what most users would encounter in regular use.\n\n3. **User Experience**: Opening too many tabs can lead to a sluggish experience, making it difficult to manage tabs effectively. \n\nIn summary, while you can theoretically open thousands of tabs, practical usability and performance will dictate a more manageable number.",
